                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d702">
                <head>No. 698.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Blaine</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Fish</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1881-05-26">
                            <hi rend="italic">May</hi> 26, 1881</date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 213.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have to acknowledge the receipt of your No.
                    397, and to express my satisfaction respecting your course in the case of
                    Eberhard, <pb facs="1284" n="1160" xml:id="pg_1160"/> whose emigration to the
                    United States would evidently have proved undesirable.</p>
                <p>The communication of the facts mentioned in your No. 400, in the case of the
                    Oliver family, to the collector of customs at New York is approved.</p>
                <p>A copy of your No. 403 will be sent to the State board of charities, New York, as
                    you suggest.</p>
                <p>I am, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>JAMES G. BLAINE.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
